<font color="#FF0000">RUSHED THOUGHTS ON PTSD.</font><br>
<tt>Wed Sep 24 23:03:43 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Brothers, (and I think we are), PTSD is a strange assortment of symptoms that are different from one to another. The experience &quot;outside the realm of normal human experience&quot; is the glue that brings it all together. After that it is all yours.  Car Crash survivors to jungle veterans, child abuse kids m(a different type of PTSD) to combat wiery vets, each story is as unique as each individual.  Most shrinks can't or won't understand this, which complicates the problem.<br><br>
Clearly the stories of war caused for most of you the PTSD symptoms that you have. The degree of them, from minor to moderate to severe, is varying from vet to vet.  There is nothing known as to why Bill got PTSD from a certain firefight and John didn't. Nothing.<br><br>
What is more important, unless you are somekind of Freudian analyst, is to come to terms with whatever it is that you have, and Deal with HOW YOU COPE WITH IT.  For some, there is some psychiatric medications (tofranil?) that help, for others who have panic attacks, (xanax) other meds help.  The key to this picture is (1) acknowledgement that you have &quot;it&quot; and (2) finding a treatment regiment that works for you. What helped Bill may be poison for John, Etc. Etc.<br><br>
A vet friend of mine related this to me. He came home, 24 hours fresh from the bush, to Tennesssee. He told his dad he was fine. The next morning while eating breakfast the tractor next door started up (no muffler) and he dove for the deck.  Fine eh? said his dad. Nothing else.  <br><br>
The point is that you have to learn how to adapt. Time is the ultimate cure.  After 30 years if you still have symptoms then that is a lie too.  Medication is called for after a year or two.  You have to get over the &quot;manly&quot; point of this. I&gt;E&gt; real man don't get PTSD. That is a crock.  I could write on this for another hour, but my 15 year old daughter is stomping on my foot, saying it is her time on the computer. So, being the politically correct father, and &quot;needing acceptance&quot;, I have to give up my Mac.  Adios for now, my compadre's, this could be the best thread yet on this site.
